  Let <fr:tex>(X,  \le )</fr:tex> be a preordered set. The class of <fr:link
href="axt-001Z.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001Z">upward closed</fr:link>
  sets on <fr:tex>X</fr:tex> form a topology.
</fr:p><fr:p><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>420</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>9</fr:day></fr:date><fr:parent>axt-004J</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>
      The entire set <fr:tex>X</fr:tex> is trivially upward closed. Let <fr:tex>U, V  \subseteq  X</fr:tex> be
      two upward closed sets. Given an element <fr:tex>x  \in  U  \cap  V</fr:tex> falling in
      both, any <fr:tex>y  \ge  x</fr:tex> must also fall in both by the upward closure
      properties of <fr:tex>U</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>V</fr:tex>, which is to say that <fr:tex>U  \cap  V</fr:tex> is itself
      upward closed. This is to say that the class of upward closed sets is
      closed under finite intersection.
    </fr:p>
    <fr:p>
      Let <fr:tex>\{  V_i  \} _{i  \in  I}</fr:tex> be an arbitrary family of upward closed sets
      and let <fr:tex>x  \in   \bigcup _{i  \in  I} V_i</fr:tex>. This means that there exists some
      <fr:tex>k  \in  I</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>x  \in  V_k</fr:tex>. Any <fr:tex>y  \ge  x</fr:tex> must also be in
      <fr:tex>V_k</fr:tex> by its upward closure property which is to say any such <fr:tex>y</fr:tex>
      will also fall in the union <fr:tex>\bigcup _{i  \in  I} V_i</fr:tex>. Therefore, the class
      of upward closed sets is closed under arbitrary union.
    </fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:contributions></fr:contributions><fr:context></fr:context><fr:related><fr:tree
